= section "Superlatives" do
  %p A superlative may be made by attaching the prefix #{t "най-", "nai-"} to the comparative form: #{t "найвелише", "naivelíśe"} “greatest”, #{t "найболше", "naibólśe"} “largest”, #{t "найхуже", "naihúźe"} “worst”. When an adjective begins with a vowel, that vowel takes its iotafied form, though the й in the prefix is still redundantly written: авине “clear” → #{t "найяунше", "naiiáunśe"}.
  %p This prefix is to be avoided when at all possible; it is considered poor style to overuse it.

= section "Other Degrees and Prefixes" do
  %p In addition to the comparative and superlative, Novegradian adjectives can mark two other degrees—the intensive and the excessive. Like the superlative, these are both prefixial and optional. However, unlike the superlative, their use is encouraged, as overuse of adverbs to express the same concept is considered poor style.
  %p The prefix #{t "пре-", "pre-"} means “very”, and intensifies the quality already expressed by the adjective. It is attached to the absolute degree of the adjective (i.e., the base definite or indefinite form, never a comparative base) and is generally unstressed. On a few adjectives, it is almost required in place of seperate adverbials (e.g., #{t "прекрасне", "prekrásne"} “very beautiful”, almost never #{t "**велем красне", "vélem krásne"}).
  %p The stressed prefix #{t "во-", "vó-"} means “too (much)”, and indicates excess. It is added to either the base form of an adjective or the comparative stem (but only if the comparative stem is formed by consonant mutation): #{t "воблизе", "vóblize"} / #{t "воблиғье", "vóbliğje"} “too close”.
  %p If either prefix is added to an adjective beginning with a vowel, that vowel takes its iotafied form: #{t "преявине", "preiávine"} “very evident”. If they are added to an adjective that already has a lexical prefix with no functional load (e.g., #{t "приглубе", "priglúbe"} “deep”, since **глубе does not exist), the lexical prefix may drop in many cases: #{t "воглубе", "vóglube"} “too deep”, not #{t "*воприглубе", "*vópriglube"}.
  %p There is one other adjective degree known as the “trial superlative”, formed by the prefix #{t "тре-", "tre-"}. It is frequently and productively used in literature and storytelling, but has very limited functionality elsewhere.
  %p In literature and liturgical contexts, it is used to indicate a superlative, though it also has connotations of great importance: #{t "тресуете", "tresuéte"} “thrice-holy, most holy”. It is also used hyperbolically, as in the common folkloric opening #{t "На Тредевитиех Жемлах, на Тредежитѣѣм Царестўѣ", "Na Tredevítijeh Źemláh, na Tredeźítěiěm Cárestuě"} “In the Thrice-Nine Lands, in the Thrice-Ten Tsardom”, used to refer to a far away land.

%hr.footnote

%p 1) Dual nouns take plural adjective agreement, with one exception: adjectives modifying a noun in the dative/instrumental dual take the ending #{t "-ама", "-ama"}, rather than the plural -ами. This is generally not considered to be a true dual declension, but rather simply a case of “ending spreading”, as is also occasionally seen in the dative/instrumental of personal names. Both of these phenomena are discussed more in depth later in this grammar.
